	<!-- message -->
	<p>The "rotation" you are talking about is 3 seconds every four minutes. You honestly mean to tell me that you can't handle that? Just watch the gem, when it refreshes, hit it again. Not exactly rocket science. Depending on the situation, we've had clerics doing BoV cycles and wizards doing SS cycles, they've been able to cope just fine, I'm sure shaman will too.<br />
<br />
And Giac, I have played a shaman on raids, even on Quarm. You have spell slots you can open there. Drop malos, let mages take care of resist debuffs. Failing that, only one shaman needs malos up. The rest of you don't. The shaman on malos can drop slow. So there's a slot right there. Also, why do you have DA up as well as Nadox? It implies that you are curing specific people outside of your group. That means that you <b>do</b> have spell gem allocated to an infrequent "rotation", just as panther would be. Lot's of guilds did Quarm just fine with only 8 spell gems prior to the release of OoW, so I'm pretty sure that you will be able to use the 9th gem for a spell as powerful as panther.<br />
<br />
And Giac, you are misrepresenting the Quarm situation. Firstly, its unlikely that Quarm is going to quad for full on an MT in a guild capable of doing him (and in any case, panther would completely remove the possibility of that one rounding a decently equiped tank). Secondly, allthough Quarm has a lot of AEs, you don't need to cure everything. True, some people have horrible resists, but given the choice between them dying and the MT dying, I know which I would choose and probably you do to. Since you obviously dont know anything about this, the size of quarm makes AEtaunt pretty dicy on him, so keeping the MA alive is the number one priority. If the folks in your guild have crap resists, then take some time to gear them up properly for the content first, the problem will go away then.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Your primary banner that you've been parading around in this thread is that every tank is going to want this spell for the 1500hp, yet the spell it self is contradictory. The HP component and its retardedly short duration gives the dilemma where encounters are going to be designed requiring the tank to have 1500 more HP, yet the crit component is surely better being cast on a DPS class.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>You are misrepresenting me again. I said that MT's will want it, not all tanks. True, the crit component isn't necessary in a raid situation, but it doesnt hurt. And outside of raids, in groups, the spell will be handy on nameds as well (where the added dps will be far more usefull).</p>
	
	
	
